recordings.loc: Drumawill, Fermanagh and Omagh, Northern Ireland
recordings.rmk:
This recording features a male Blackcap that frequently mimicked a Blackbird. The Blackbird can be heard singing in the background and the notes that it produces are those mimicked by the Blackcap.  The interesting point is that the Blackcap is mimicking the Blackbird in 'real time', although it could also know the Blackbird's song from memory. The full recording exceeded 40 minutes, during which the Blackcap copied the Blackbird several times.   
 
The recorder was left near the Blackcap.  I was not there to watch the bird.  Perhaps a Robin approached the device because the opening high-pitched ‘seeh’ calls are, to my ears, like a Robin. You can hear them at 0:01, 0:05, 0:07, 0:09, 0:12, 0:14 and occasionally later, such as at 0:45. Another sound is more intriguing – a Bullfinch? This call can be heard at 0:02 (three times in quick succession), 0:04 (twice) and later, such as at 0:10. Or is this the Blackcap? In other words, the Blackcap is responsible for all the sound on the clip.  

Blackcap song-bursts typically last around five or six seconds and build in volume to a peak before ending in a few clearer, more fluty (or musical) notes. There are several typical song-bursts in the clip and some have the Blackbird mimicry at the start, such as 0:46, 0:55, 1:02 and 1:09. The mimicry is seamless and is woven into the opening of the Blackcap's song-burst.  On a handful of occasions the Blackcap also inserted Blackbird mimicry among a more rambling burst.  

Blackcaps also utter long, sustained bursts that can exceed a minute or more of continuous sound. Stephen Hewitt, BTO, reckons that the long bursts are connected to mate attraction (the long bursts are ecstatic, almost breathless), whereas the short bursts indicate that the singing male has a mate and (probably) that a nest has been constructed and a breeding attempt is underway. The same explanation is contained in THE HANDBOOK OF BRITISH BIRDS (1940, Witherby et al.). On page 80 of vol. 2, the text reads: 'fullest song, best heard early in the season, is ... more intense, varied and sustained (10-30 seconds or more) and, at best, of striking richness and beauty, usually beginning with rich warbling and bursting out into much louder finish. Song frequently mimetic. (Howard emphasises deterioration of song after arrival of female; during actual display it consists mainly of high-pitched squealing and mimickry).'

Examples of long song-bursts are at 0:18 (ten seconds duration) and 0:31 (14 seconds duration). 

Also on the clip are GOLDCREST 0:28 and WILLOW WARBLER 0:08 and 0:29.

recordings.loc: Ards and North Down, Northern Ireland
recordings.rmk:
This clip demonstrates male Blackcap habit of often singing almost continuously in spring, especially when the breeding  population is back and activities are in full swing.  Males 'punch above their weight' because they are defending territory as well as looking for (or guarding) a breeding partner. On this clip the song runs virtually uninterrupted from the 29th second until I edited the end at around two minutes. In life, the bird carried on for about another two minutes. 

I'd like to quote an interesting observation from Stephen Hewitt, BTO, about when Blackcaps indulge in almost continuous singing - and when they switch back to conventional singing. Stephen wrote:  I find that prolonged continuous song is reasonably common in Blackcap males. Once they switch to intermittent bursts of one or two phrases I regard it as time to search for active nests, although they can occasionally give the prolonged song even when they have an active nest.


In this clip, from the 29th second, the breaks between song bursts last barely one second. The recording opens with a Blackbird [0:02, 0:05, 0:10] but the Blackcap [first song burst at 0:03, then 0:07, 0:13] is oblivious to the Blackbird's singing and often the two species overlap. In a lucky touch, the Blackcap flies and perches closer to the recorder. Its wing-beats are audible at 0:12 and, this time flying away, at 0:26. Other species in the background are CHIFFCHAFF at 0:26; HOODED CROW at 1:41 and RAVEN at 1:42. The BLACKBIRD is also engaging in song wars with a rival - both can be heard taking it in turns to sing, such as at 1:56 and from 2:06.

Groene Pollen, 22 mei. from:"Zangers op Terschelling in 1987",2004, Rombout de Wijs.

s avonds/'s nachts. Zwartkop. De luide melodieuze zang van deze soort wordt vergezeld door o.a. Koekoek, Winterkoning, Boomkruiper, Tuinfluiter en wat menselijke dorpsgeluiden. from: "Sprosser bei Gützkow", 2005, Rombout de Wijs. Sinds lang heb ik een zwak voor de zang van de Noordse Nachtegaal, Sprosser in het Duits. Meer nog dan onze gewone Nachtegaal spreekt zijn zang mij aan: voller en lager van klank, wat trager en met karakteristieke ratels aan het eind van elke zangstrofe. Toen ik dan in de gelegenheid was om met een aantal collega's van Natuurmonumenten een bezoek brengen aan het dal van de Peene in voormalig Oost Duitsland, heb ik die kans gegrepen om zijn zang op te nemen. Het bezoek was van 10-14 juni 2005, van alle 4 overnachtingen heb ik een deel gewijd aan het opnemen van geluiden. Naast de zang van ze soort, heb ik ook andere soorten opgenomen, maar op vrijwel alle opnames zijn ook Sprosser te horen. De opnames zijn gemaakt rond onze verblijfplaats in GUtzkow. In de directe omgeving hiervan zijn verschillende voorbeelden aanwezig van voormalige landbouwgebieden, die nu een natuurbestemming hebben gekregen, het doel van het werkbezoek.

These verses are followed by more typical short verses with whistles at the end of each. Note that the recording is missing two short verses (12 seconds) at 57s where I move a little closer to the bird and rustled.

recordings.loc: Chilcombe Bottom, Bath and North East Somerset, England
recordings.rmk:
Singing from a hedgerow ash tree. The track opens with a Blackbird followed immediately by the Blackcap mimicking this species. There are further occasions when the Blackcap mimicks Blackbirds such as 1:43.5, 4:33.0, 4:43.2 and 6:26.0. At 6:48.5 either a Blackbird or Mistle Thrush sounds like it is imitated. There are probably further examples of mimicry in there, a number of repeated phrases are certainly reminiscent of Song Thrush song and a few sections remind me of Siskins (5:02.1, 5:37.8 and 6:15.2).

 Most of the verses starts with a variety of phrases and finish with the typical fluty Blackcap notes. Towards the end the bird sings more subdued phrases before flying off. 
Recorded with an Olympus LS-12 and Sennheiser ME66 handheld. 
EQ lightly adjusted below 1400 Hz to remove some handling noise and distant vehicles.

You may find the time references do not accurately point to the actual referred times, as discussed in [Forum topic 25398](https://www.xeno-canto.org/forum/topic/25398).
Zoom H5 et Superlux S 502

recordings.rmk:
Blackcap song from about 50 minutes after the bird first started singing. Among its repertoire - and not uncommonly from among the repertoire of other Blackcaps that I have listened to - there is the occasional  phrase that to my ears sounds a bit like a Nightingale.  I know Nightingale song from several trips in spring to Catalonia.  The phrase in question can be heard just after 0:10. A Buzzard calls at 1:03 (four calls over the next five seconds).

Blackcaps indulge in mimickry. One singer that, unfortunately, I failed to record, began his song with several perfect Blackbird phrases. So much so that I was astonished when he broke into typical voice - it was a Blackcap.  In this recording, it strikes me that the opening three seconds could well be a sample of Robin. If you heard say, just the first three seconds, would you not think you were listening to a Robin?

recordings.loc: Strickland's Glen, North Down, Northern Ireland
recordings.rmk:
This is the same male that featured in XC552441. Unlike the latter recording, there is no rival singing in competition. This individual Blackcap has a trademark 'yodel' that it uses in almost all its verses. The yodel (for want of a better word) is included in this clip - but it was noticeably absent when the bird was involved in direct competition with a rival. The yodel - a kind of alternating change in scale, a bit like a boogie-woogie riff on a piano, can be heard at 0:07; 0:18; 0:30; 0:42. Unlike in XC552441, the Blackcap had largely ceased its mimicry of Blackbird. Nonetheless, you can again here Blackbird samples at 0:15 and 0:26. For some reason, the Blackbird samples from this passage of singing are much more embedded in the overall composition - and could easily be overlooked. 

From this and other Blackcaps I sometimes hear a fleeting haunting sound that reminds me of Nightingale. I do not know if the birds are actually copying Nightingales - that they presumably hear when the two species overlap on migration in Spain and maybe southern France - or create the sound themselves. The sound I mean is at 0:38 and lasts roughly two seconds. 

Other species in the clip are: Wren (0:10) and Great Tit (0:13; 0:20; 0:26).

recordings.loc: Ireland (near  Bangor), Ards and North Down, Northern Ireland
recordings.rmk:
This recording is an extract from several hours of vocal arm-wrestling between two rival male Blackcaps. Competition seems to be at maximum intensity, heightened further because at least one female Blackcap was in the area. Maybe she was partnered to one of the males? Both males had been in the area for over a fortnight. Initially - and presumably before any female arrived - the song was less prolonged and lacked much mimicry of other species.  Competition seems to have spurred the males to 'raise their game'. Hence the song bursts are longer and more sustained, with bits of mimicry included as some kind of added embellishment. Six verses are on the clip. The duration of most exceeds the five or six seconds that is typical of song bursts when the birds first arrive in early April (such as XC552444).  Two bursts are over ten seconds; one lasts 26 seconds (from 1:03).  Mimicry of Blackbird can be heard at 0:34-36 (start of third verse); 0:42-44 (start of fourth verse); 0:52-54 (end of fourth verse). In these - and other instances, not on the clip - mimicry is either at the beginning or end of a song burst.  The verbal battle has the briefest of breaks. I assume the breaks are only because one male is pausing to check if its rival is still singing. Unlike other songbirds that indulge in singing contests, Blackcaps sing against each other and overlap their efforts. They do not take it in turns - as Robins, Dunnocks, Blackbirds and others do. The same Blackcap can be heard at XC552452 - but singing on his own, when he seems less animated. The rival either went quiet or moved elsewhere. 

A Woodpigeon utters its classic broadcast sequence at 0:15 until the 24th second.
